It’s raining today in Los Angeles and nothing brings me more joy than an LA downpour. So I’m gonna be in this cozy ass room, snuggling my Piggy™️ @saturdaysoria all day long. This Christmas tree (which is no longer up bc the I shot it in October and everything online is a lie) is the worst Christmas tree I have ever done. I say this because I am normally good at decorating trees (see: Gay). This shoot came at a time where I was too busy to prep/plan/shop so I went to Target the day before assuming they’d have Christmas ornaments AND THEY DIDN’T, GIRLFRIEND. So I had to make due with random holiday things from their $1/garbage section. The upside to all this is I decorated the whole tree for less than $200. Most trees you see online have thousands of dollars worth of ornaments on them bc ornaments are expensive and you need like 200x more of them than you think you do to make your tree look good. Anyway, this tree is fine/passable for a photo but we all know it will be a stain on my Tree Decorating GPA for the rest of my life. But HARK let us all rejoice in my failure! Even literal Christmas Tree Professionals falter sometimes! I must and will do better! Happy December to Remember to all who celebrate! Photo by @tramp.studio #Bungalowlando #HoHoHolando #ChristmasTree

The last few days have been rough - I’m fine, dealing with some anxiety issues that are affecting my short-term memory. I’m just trying to get through these last few weeks of the year and I have some plans/strategies for how to better handle my workload and my general inclination to worry ALL DAY LONG ABOUT LITERALLY EVERYTHING. Like everyone, I have a ton of different jobs and responsibilities and sometimes I feel like I’m drowning in them and can’t breathe. But I’m fine! (I promise, I am very proactive with handling mental health stuff and have been on the upswing all year). I found out this week about a few people in my life struggling with health issues, mental and otherwise. Life is fucking hard. And this can be such a hard time of the year. The darkness. The feeling that you’re supposed to feel or be a certain way. Check in with friends and when in doubt just send an “I love you” text. This is a good, magical time but illness and struggle don’t take a break for the holidays. Check in on your people. ❤️ Photo by @tramp.studio

MAJOR LIFE NEWS! Today I’m filming my first-ever scripted commercial! I know that might sound dumb, but it’s a different kind of on-camera work than I’ve ever done. Yes, I’ve been doing TV for more than ten years and yes, I’ve done a lot of #SponCon (as myself) but I’ve never gotten the chance to exercise this muscle before. I’m not really an actor per se, but a goal of mine for 2023 is to do more one-off hosting gigs and commercial work so this is a HUGE opportunity for me. The reasons I’m going after these goals are many. Firstly, I’m an innately shy person so doing things where I have to be outgoing and friendly on set helps me realize I’m actually pretty dynamic and likable. It helps me open up and gives me confidence. Second, it’s a challenge and I like to be challenged in new ways to keep my creative energy fresh. Third, acting/hosting/on camera work is fun - it’s a whole room of high school drama nerds working together to make something they’re all excited about. Anyway, wish me luck! Or come break both my legs or whatever! And if you’re a brand or organization that needs on-camera talent, you can contact my reps at the link-in-bio. And tune in to the 95th Academy Awards on March 12, 2023 to watch me accept the first Oscar ever given to an Idiot From A Commercial™️ for my GROUNDBREAKING WORK. The Londo Lodge family room is ready for a cozy Christmas Eve! I made the decision to spend the holiday up here by myself, which was tough but just felt right this year. Firstly, I cannot comprehend how it’s Christmas already - it feels like this year went by so quickly and I’m not ready to do a big celebration like this again so soon. Second, these few holiday weeks of the year are the only ones where people aren’t emailing me constantly asking me for things all day long. Like the one peaceful moment in the year that normally gets jam packed with family and friends. Which I love. But I was just feeling like I needed a minute to breathe and do some passion projects I’ve been too busy to tackle. Maybe I will make a painting. Maybe I’ll write some of the stories that have been rumbling around in my head down on paper. Maybe I’ll just use the extra time to snuggle my Snuggy Piggy™️ @saturdaysoria since she guilts me constantly for not providing enough snuggles. WHO KNOWS THE WORLD IS OUR OYSTER. My family visited last week which was a huge treat. We did all the things (cookies, a trip into Yosemite Valley, fancy dinners). Here’s to the ever evolving traditions every family has and being open to them changing over time. And here’s to taking a breather when you need one. Happy ALL THE HOLIDAYS to everyone! I’m Gay! Goodbye! #HoHoHolando #HolidayDecorating #Recharge

Well, something VERY exciting has happened. After more than a year, tens of thousands of dollars in inspection/permit fees, and other county related expenses, Londo Lodge is finally permitted for vacation rental! My kitchen renovation is slated to start  February 7, so if you want a trip to a wintry wonderland before then, I’d jump on it! I have my first booking on Friday, so I’m heading up to put the final finishing touches on the house. Of course I’m biased, but this is by far best vacation rental in town. The beds are luxe and have luscious bedding. The decor and wall colors are beautiful. There’s design inspo everywhere. The baths are stocked with natural and eco friendly products from @captainblankenship and the kitchen is huge and perfect for people who love cooking together (and @peetscoffee is your FREE GIFT WITH PURCHASE so you don’t even have to bring coffee). Oh, and it’s still decorated for Christmas which is so glowy and fun. I care about how things look and feel and smell. So this isn’t gonna be one of those Airbnbs where you show up and there’s green dish liquid in the hand soap dispensers (I opted for @thymesfragrances Frasier Fir hand soap bc I’m a candle woman). I’ve worked really hard to make this a place where my family and friends could come be cozy and relaxed. Where they could go into Yosemite National Park (two miles from the house) or just stay inside enjoying the peaceful surroundings. Head to the link-in-bio and book your stay! #LondoLodge

If you can’t afford a gut reno, paint, furnishings, and hardware can go a long way. I love this bathroom makeover I did with @kohler last year. Today, I’m on @em_henderson’s blog with a FULL home tour showing Londo Lodge at its various stages of the design process. I finally have it up on @airbnb but I wanted to make sure it was a place I was proud for people to see before I opened it up. Getting it there took two full years and a lot of blood (literally), sweat (literally), and tears (literally, many). My life, demeanor, even my body have completely changed in the last six months - things have just gotten lighter and easier. And I think a lot of it is that I’m not stuck in a huge cabin trying to renovate it with a shoestring budget while being totally overwhelmed by work and in a career/covid induced depression. Living in the house and renovating it alone ended up being very hard on my body, leading to a fifty pound weight gain, depression, a stress injury on my knee, and planter fasciitis on both my feet. BUT THE STORY HAS A VERY HAPPY ENDING. I’m all better now, my house is beautiful, and I’m so proud of how much I was able to do with so little cash. Check out my post at the link-in-bio to read about this harrowing journey and get some tips on how to improve your home if you’re like me and can’t afford the renovation of your dreams just yet. Photo @tramp.studio #LondoLodge #BathroomMakeover #BeforeAndAfter

Oooof, you guys. This week got me. I got food poisoning Monday night and it lasted ALL WEEK. Like not normal food poisoning. My whole body was in excruciating pain, I had a migraine, my bones hurt, and I was too weak to stand up. I didn’t sleep for days and I felt like death. But I’m finally better and sooooooo happy. One thing that’s good about getting sick, like reeaaaaally sick, the kind where you can’t move, is that it shows you that it is literally possible to lay on your sofa doing absolutely nothing sometimes. I tend to forget that. In other news, my LA dining room has undergone a very pretty @clarepaint makeover. My goal with my Clare partnership is to share ideas people can try to elevate their paint jobs. In here, I knew I wanted a white ceiling but again was faced with these luscious, curvy walls that ease into the ceiling. So I painted a big oval over the dining table and I’m really pleased with how it came out. You can read more in depth about the process and the design of the room at the link-in-bio! And never eat chicken salad you found in your fridge if you’re not sure how old it is. 😳 #ClareCollective #Bungalowlando #DiningRoom

I have been writing things on The Internet since I was *THIS BIG* 👉[*points to picture slideshow*]. Here’s what I learned. Firstly, I learned that the past is dumb but the future is probably going to be even dumber. I learned that you’re never too young to be told you’re “too old for those Bieber bangs” (I was 24). I learned that caffeine and malt liquor combined together can be delicious and exciting (see Sparks can). I learned that if you take a strong stance on something, you need to be ready to get publicly yodeled at. But mostly I learned the value of sharing your story in a vulnerable way, without pretense. I’ve been blogging since I got out of school in 2007. But for the past couple of years finding a rhythm with my writing has become more and more challenging. First, I had a few big jobs get in the way (being a creative director at a startup, writing my book, developing and shooting a TV show, almost dying in my Snowmageddon cabin like five times, and so on). Second, blogging totally changed. And social media came into existence. I’ve enjoyed sharing my life through the lens of my various home renovation projects, but have felt stymied by the amount of logistics that go into just ONE blog post about design: concepting and designing a space, paying for (or securing sponsorships for) the makeover, physically doing the makeover, styling the space, hiring a photographer, waiting for edited photos, resizing those photos, uploading them, AND THEN FINALLY GETTING TO THE WRITING PART. So I’ve decided to break from the limitations I’ve spent the last twelve years observing and create a space for myself to write about whatever I want, free from the constraints of my Interior “Design Expert” online/TV persona. In short, I’ve created a Substack. And if you’ve been watching from afar, wishing we lived in a world with less sponsored content, this is your chance to support that notion by paying for content (by subscribing!). Head on over to my Substack, The Lost Arrow, by hitting the link-in-bio. And get ready for VERY IMPORTANT essays on topics ranging from my feelings on parenting a pit bull to why I hate tapas. Goodbye! #TheLostArrow

Do you love to travel but hate the following things: 1. Thinking 2. Planning 3. Logistics? HONESTLY SAME. So I’m partnering with @trovatrip to coordinate a trip we can take TOGETHER in the coming year (where somebody else does all the planning and legwork). In order for me to figure out where people want to go, what their budgets are, and what they want to do, I am sharing a survey (link-in-bio) to hone in on the perfect vacation destination. I’ve spoken a bit about building moments (the time leading up to reaching a goal) and payoff moments (when you finally see a goal realized). My book “Get It Together!, published five years ago, was one of the biggest payoff moments I’ve ever had. I still carry the love with me from the incredible launch parties I threw in collaboration with @westelm in New York and Los Angeles, my two favorite American cities (and the ones where I’ve spent the most time). If you were there, you know these events were blockbuster crowded and so so much fun. It’s so rare to be on the receiving end of that and so very worth all the labor of writing a book to get there. A little back story on the book itself: I was approached by a few different publishers but I ended up deciding to go with one where I had a personal connection. I met @laduelala at @cornelluniversity where we both lived in Risley, a notoriously offbeat program house for artists, performers, and weirdos of all kinds. Personal connections and loyalty are a big thing for me, so even though I could have gone with a publisher that offered a bigger advance, I went with someone I knew understood my vision and would let me write the book I wanted to write. I cannot say enough good things about Holly. She’s the type of New York intellectual I always wanted to be. Her taste and sensibility comes from a lifetime of fascination and support for artists. In a funny coincidence, she also edited a book by someone who is related to me (by marriage): @ryanpfluger worked with Holly to create his absolutely stunning book of portraits and stories “Holding Space,” which came out last year and is a must-buy. I’m so thankful to Holly for seeking out and amplifying queer voices. I miss working with photographer @zekeruelas so much - after we made this book he moved to Nashville (if you need a photographer he is HIGHLY recommended). I still have the suit I hand painted hanging in my closet and I love how crazy it is. Hoping to have a reason to paint another one soon. I’ve had offers to write another book and it’s def on my radar, just trying to come up with a great concept. STAY TUNED. #GetItTogetherOrlando

I was born in a Central Valley town called Merced in a small house my parents renovated themselves before we moved to Yosemite when I was five years old. We had a great big (to me at the time) living room and my parents had enormous speakers connected to a vintage turntable. Pictured here are my siblings, leaning their heads against those speakers. I have no idea what they’re actually listening to, but in my head, in the memories that this photograph has allowed me to fabricate over the years, they’re listening to the first grown up album (meaning not Raffi) I ever remember listening to, Tina Turner’s 1984 masterpiece “Private Dancer.” I have few memories of that house, but one clear one is dancing my ass off with my siblings to all the tracks on that album, notably “1984,” which is basically the best song to wiggle around like a backup dancer to. We loved “What’s Love Got to Do With It” Tina. We loved The Who’s “Tommy” Acid Queen Tina. And Tina introduced us to the brilliance of the beautiful Angela Bassett in the 1993 biopic. Tina is THE diva for our family. This is going to sound weird, but I’ve had a secret fear of her death for years. It sounds ridiculous but it was something I tried never to speak of because I worried I’d believe it into being. I don’t care about many celebrities, but Tina just holds a special place for me. Her beauty and strength, her resilience, charm, her ability to be otherworldly in her power yet maintain softness in the face of hardness. What a loss. It’s an odd feeling to get older and see these stalwarts - these cherished beings we’ve held on high, who have spoken directly into our souls - pass. Icons like Tina become sort of a personal point of reference, a polar force that reminds you where you have been and where you are going. I am thankful for the joy and dancing brought into my life by Tina Turner and genuinely very upset she’s gone. (And yes I realize this is a pretty crazy reaction to the death of a complete stranger). Planning to spend the long weekend honoring the Queen by listening to her music. ❤️ #TinaTurner #RIPTinaTurner #SimplyTheBest

I’ve been up here a few weeks and the news isn’t great. The first week I was here the water stopped working and it took a week for the well dude to figure out how to make it work again. Right now I’m waiting on a few big checks from projects I did in late spring (thanks you to all my partners this year I’ve gotten to work on some really fun projects). Honestly, I’m pretty bummed the kitchen is taking so long - it’s been demo’d since January. But it is what it is and I’m just trying to lean into the adventure aspect of it and try to find joy in a challenging time. This house has brought me so much stress but being up here is allowing me to see the magic of my surroundings again - the lupine and ferns in my yard are going crazy, the dogwood trees that got knocked down by the snow have started growing back, there’s just s lot of life up here. The nation’s slowest renovation continues! The Londo Lodge kitchen cabinets arrived today! Thanks to @rebeccazajac and @littleshoppeinthedesert for making it happen! #LondoLodge

The Londo Lodge kitchen cabinets are ON SITE! I began this renovation three years ago. The @bertazzoni_official appliances were selected and the design completely finished THREE YEARS AGO. The @fireclaytile has been sitting in my garage for two full years. As have all the @kohler fixtures. I’m not gonna lie, it kinda sucks doing what I do and watching your friends do much bigger, more expansive renovations in much quicker timeframes. BUT COMPARISON IS THE THIEF OF JOY so I will not be letting that knowledge rain on my parade. Three years is a long time. I was 38. Now I’m 41. The pandemic was just getting started. Now it’s here forever? The main reason this project has taken so long? Money. And for that reason I’m being really open about all this - most people have to save and save and save to make their renovations dreams come true, myself included. Yes I am getting a lot for free and I’m so thankful. But it feels like every element that is coming into this space took months to arrive. It took me six months to save for the windows and doors and another ten months for them to arrive. It took me a full year to save for the cabinets and they took about two months to arrive. And honestly I still don’t know what I’m doing about countertops because the original sponsor backed out when the project started dragging. One thing at a time. This project has been a slog and if I had to do it all over again I probably wouldn’t - now I’m just trying to finish so my sponsors aren’t waiting another full year for images. It’s stretching me far beyond my financial comfort zone and has been the main reason I’ve avoided coming up here since we demo’d the old kitchen out in January. When a project takes this long you kind of lose sight of the exciting part, the part where you’re imagining what it’ll be like to be in your beautifully designed finished space. But having the cabinets come in thanks to @rebeccazajac @littleshoppeinthedesert  I’m starting to remember there was a point to all this, getting my dream kitchen. Here’s to all the other slow burn renovators out there - we’ll get there eventually! #LondoLodge

This little Londo Lodge Lounge Land brings me so much joy. In all my years designing, I’d never had to design stairs from scratch. So this was a bit of a challenge (the angles, code regulations, and even just figuring out the rail components to buy was a lot to wrap my head around). The old orange peel texture post was a bummer so I wrapped it in veneer and added some millwork flourishes to make it match the same craftsman style I plan to overlay onto this blank canvas of a house over time (it’s a big house so making the full transition is gonna take a while). For now, the staircase feels a bit disjointed from the 90s contemporary style of this big box house, but I just love the character and warmth the wood brings. I had one carpenter refuse to build the railing because he thought my design was ugly. I mean, sorry not sorry but I think that guy was an absolute fool. Luckily my homie @swabyjustin saved the day by driving up from Joshua Tree to fix the errors a previous installer had made with the rails and the flooring. And now this little corner is a favorite lounge space. Satie usually wakes me up to go out early in the morning so when we’re done with potty duty I normally come over here and rest until the coffee is brewed and my brain turns on. LONDO LODGE KITCHEN UPDATE: I’ve been up here full time since September and the kitchen is getting CLOSE. The @fireclaytile backsplash is finally in, as of last night I’ve installed all the cabinet doors and drawers (hardware next), I’ve finished rebuilding the peninsula to my taste, the windows and doors are almost fully trimmed out, the @kohler faucets are in, the countertops are in, WE ARE SO CLOSE! Next steps, we need to grout the tile, install the @bertazzoni_official appliances, and do a TON of finishing work. The kitchen has been in a state of almost done for weeks now and I’d be lying if I said I wasn’t completely burnt out. The kitchen has been demo’d since January, planned for three full years, and these appliances and materials have been in my garage for two and a half years. I’ve spent the better part of this YEAR up here waiting for people to come help me only to have them blow me off and constantly reschedule, trapping me alone in a house in the woods trying to figure things out myself. It’s been wildly educational and I’m so thankful for all I’ve learned. One thing I found I’m good at: MILLWORK! The cabinets all came with machine-made side panels I had to remake for layout reasons that ended up feeling so much richer and more historic than the originals. I based the design for much of my trim work on traditional craftsman wainscoting and I love the old world charm it adds to the kitchen. I finally got the lighting on a dimmer, which had made it less of a football stadium in here but I’m still not fully sure I didn’t make a mistake by including so much lighting (there’s six more sconces coming in LOL). This has definitely been a learning experience I won’t forget but it’s also been absolutely terrible for my physical and mental health. Being this isolated, this alone in a project, feeling unsure of when it would be over or if the people I hired would ever show up, watching my bank account hover at zero all year because the second I get paid I have to pay for something for the kitchen, has been less than fun. Here’s hoping the rest of the job gets done quickly so I we can all move on! #LondoLodge #ImGayInTheWoods #LondosLongestReno

HARK! A January miracle has occurred! Badger Pass, a short 40 minute drive from Londo Lodge, has opened for the season! This place is near and dear to my heart as it’s the place where orlandDAD taught me how to ski when I was five. The Yosemite School (K-8), where I went, busses their kids up here every Wednesday for Ski Day. If you’re a new skier or if you don’t feel like paying $300 for a Tahoe lift ticket, I cannot recommend this historic ski area enough. It’s a small hill so don’t expect Heavenly - this is a non-pretentious ski resort for the rest of us. But it’s absolutely beautiful and such a nice thing to add to a winter Yosemite trip (the park is currently blanketed in snow). Tickets are $38 kids/$64 adult which if you’ve tried to ski elsewhere you know is a bargain. The history and beauty of this place (built in 1935) are not to be missed. And a cozy fire at Londo Lodge is the best way to end the day. Be aware: you’ll need all wheel drive or chains (possibly both) to access this beauty and it’s your responsibility to keep an eye on severe weather warnings as you plan your travel. Londo Lodge is at elevation, nearly 6000 ft, so plan accordingly. Check availability by heading to the link in bio! #LondoLodge @yosemitenps #BadgerPass
